A RESOLUTION
1 Creating the House Study Committee on Pharmacy Benefits Managers and Consumer Access
2 to Prescription Medications; and for other purposes.
3 WHEREAS, according to the United States Office of Health Policy, the cost of prescription
4 drugs has increased at rates exceeding the rate of inflation each year since 2016; and
5 WHEREAS, pharmacy benefits managers administer prescription drug insurance benefits,
6 negotiate with drug manufacturers and pharmacies, and establish drug formularies and
7 pharmacy networks; and
8 WHEREAS, pharmacy benefits managers undertake practices that have been criticized and
9 investigated by industry stakeholders, including health policy experts, state attorneys general,
10 and the Federal Trade Commission; and
11 WHEREAS, such policies include leveraging vertical integration to steer patients to
12 pharmacy benefits manager affiliate pharmacies, marking up the cost of medications at
13 pharmacy benefits manager owned pharmacies, manipulating pharmacy reimbursement rates,
14 and engaging in other unfair practices that harm patients, retail pharmacies, payers, and
15 employers; and
