16 WHEREAS, in 2019, Georgia passed the first pharmacy benefits manager steering laws in
17 the nation but many believe that pharmacy benefits managers continue to steer patients to
18 pharmacy benefits manager affiliate pharmacies within this state; and
19 WHEREAS, Georgia law requires that pharmacy benefits managers publicly report drug
20 prices that are greater than 10 percent over the national average drug acquisition costs and
21 such reports have revealed markups for some medications for commercial and government
22 payers and markups of thousands of percent above the national average drug acquisition
23 costs for medications used to treat multiple sclerosis, cancer, and kidney disease, among
24 other medications; and
25 WHEREAS, a recent study by the Georgia Center for Rural Prosperity and Innovation at
26 Abraham Baldwin Agricultural College indicates that pharmacy benefits manager practices
27 pose risks to patients and independent pharmacies, including increasing the number of
28 counties in Georgia without a single pharmacy.
29 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES:
30 (1) Creation of House study committee. There is created the House Study Committee
31 on Pharmacy Benefits Managers and Consumer Access to Prescription Medications.
32 (2) Members and officers. The committee shall be composed of the following
33 members:
34 (A) The chairperson of the House Committee on Appropriations;
35 (B) The chairperson of the House Committee on Health;
36 (C) Three other members of the House of Representatives or experts on pharmacy
37 benefits managers or consumer access to prescription medication to be appointed by the
38 Speaker of the House of Representatives; and
